Kenya Central Bank Sells Dollars in Domestic Currency Market

-- B y   J o h n s t o n e   O l e   T u r a n a
-- 
2011-09-06T14:35:35Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-06/kenya-central-bank-sells-dollars-in-domestic-currency-market.html
Kenya ’s  central bank  sold dollars in
the domestic foreign-exchange market today as the shilling
approached its weakest level in 18 years, a central bank
official said.  The official declined to be identified in line with bank
policy and wouldn’t provide further details. The sale of foreign
currency by the Central Bank of Kenya is the first such
transaction since June 2, when it offered $4 million, according
to Bloomberg data.  The currency of East Africa’s biggest economy was trading
0.8 percent stronger at 94 per dollar at 5:33 p.m. in Nairobi
after earlier weakening 0.2 percent to 94.90, according to
Bloomberg data. On Aug. 9, the currency traded at 95.10, the
weakest level since March 1994.  Samson Burgei, the spokesman for the Central Bank of Kenya,
declined to comment when contacted by phone today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Johnstone Ole Turana in Nairobi at 
 jturana@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
 Paul Richardson  in Nairobi at 
 pmrichardson@bloomberg.net . 